\par \pard\plain \s0\nowidctlpar{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\cf0\kerning1\hich\af6\langfe2052\dbch\af7\afs24\lang1081\loch\f0\fs24\lang7177\ql{\i\hich\af4\dbch\af4\afs30\ai\rtlch \ltrch\loch\fs30\loch\f4
\tab \tab \'93Now the business that the first claimant sold as a going concern was engaged in the manufacture of components for motor \tab \tab cars. It was in operation as such when it was sold. Part of its operation was the manufacture, under contract, of toolings and \tab \tab components for the applicant. It was bought as a business which was \'93active and operating\'94 in its field. It was sold as a going \tab \tab concern so that \'93the trade may not be broken up and dispersed\'94. It was bought as one \'93in actual operation\'94. In my view this \tab \tab must mean that the intention of the parties was that the purchasers would be entitled to continue with any operations which \tab \tab were in progress at the time of the sale for their account. The surrounding circumstances, the factual background known to \tab \tab the parties coupled with the insertion of the restraint of trade clause in the agreement leads me to the conclusion that it was \tab \tab intended by the parties to the agreement that contracts in the process of being performed at the time of the sale were part and \tab \tab parcel of the business sold as a going concern. Further support for this view can be found in the conduct of the parties \tab \tab \tab subsequent to the signing of the contract\'85. I thus come to the conclusion that on a proper interpretation of the contract in \tab \tab \tab question the sale of the business as a going concern includes work that was in the course of execution but not yet complete \tab \tab when the business was sold. The fact that clause 1 (a) of the agreement which states that the business is sold by the first \tab \tab \tab claimant to the purchasers as a going concern for R200 000, also recites that the R200 000 represents the purchase price of \tab \tab the goodwill and the listed machinery and equipment is not intended to limit the }{\i\b\hich\af4\dbch\af4\afs30\ai\ab\rtlch \ltrch\loch\fs30\loch\f4
res vendita }{\i\hich\af4\dbch\af4\afs30\ai\rtlch \ltrch\loch\fs30\loch\f4
to the goodwill and the equipment \tab \tab to the exclusion of the work in hand which, in my view, forms part of the concept of a business sold as a going concern\'94.}
