\par \pard\plain \s0\nowidctlpar{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\cf0\kerning1\hich\af6\langfe2052\dbch\af7\afs24\lang1081\loch\f0\fs24\lang7177\ql{\i\hich\af4\dbch\af4\afs30\ai\rtlch \ltrch\loch\fs30\loch\f4
\tab \tab \'93[64] Furthermore, I am of the view that the question of whether in a particular case a business has been transferred as a \tab \tab \tab going concern is a matter for objective determination. This does not mean that the intention of the parties are irrelevant but it \tab \tab does mean that the say-so of the parties cannot be conclusive. In my view there are a number of factors that are relevant in \tab \tab determining whether or not a business has been transferred as a going concern. These may include what will happen to the \tab \tab good-will of the business, the stock-in-trade, the premises of the business, contracts with clients or customers, the workforce, \tab \tab the assets of the business, the debts of the business, whether there has been interruption of the operation of the business \tab \tab \tab and, if so, the duration thereof, whether same or similar activities are continued after the transfer or not and others. I do not \tab \tab think that the absence of anyone of these will on its own mean that the transfer of the business has not been one as a going \tab \tab concern. I would align myself with the approach adopted by the European Court of Justice when, in paragraph11,12 and 13 of \tab \tab its judgment in the }{\i\b\hich\af4\dbch\af4\afs30\ai\ab\rtlch \ltrch\loch\fs30\loch\f4
Spijker}{\i\hich\af4\dbch\af4\afs30\ai\rtlch \ltrch\loch\fs30\loch\f4
s case, it said:}
