\tab \tab \tab \tab \'93[11] \'85 It appears from the general structure of directive 77/187 and the wording of Article 1(1) that the directive \tab \tab \tab \tab aims to ensure the continuity of existing employment relationships in the framework of an economic entity, \tab \tab \tab \tab \tab irrespective of a change of owner. It follows that the decisive criterion for establishing the existence of a transfer \tab \tab \tab \tab within the meaning of the directive is whether the entity in question retains its identity.}
\par \pard\plain \s0\nowidctlpar{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\cf0\kerning1\hich\af6\langfe2052\dbch\af7\afs24\lang1081\loch\f0\fs24\lang7177\ql{\i\hich\af4\dbch\af4\afs30\ai\rtlch \ltrch\loch\fs30\loch\f4
\tab \tab \tab \tab [12] Consequently it cannot be said that there is a transfer of an enterprise, business or part of business on the \tab \tab \tab \tab \tab sole ground that its assets have been sold. On the contrary, in a case like the present, it is necessary to determine \tab \tab \tab \tab whether what has been sold is an economic entity which is still in existence, and this will be apparent from the fact \tab \tab \tab \tab that its operation is actually being continued or has been taken over by the new employer, with the same economic \tab \tab \tab \tab or similar activities.}
\par \pard\plain \s0\nowidctlpar{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\cf0\kerning1\hich\af6\langfe2052\dbch\af7\afs24\lang1081\loch\f0\fs24\lang7177\ql{\i\hich\af4\dbch\af4\afs30\ai\rtlch \ltrch\loch\fs30\loch\f4
\tab \tab \tab \tab [13] To decide whether these conditions are fulfilled it is necessary to take account of all the factual circumstances \tab \tab \tab \tab of the transaction in question, including the type of undertaking or business in question, the transfer or otherwise of \tab \tab \tab \tab tangible assets such as buildings and stocks, the value of intangible assets at the date of transfer, whether the \tab \tab \tab \tab \tab majority of the staff are taken over by the new employer, the transfer or otherwise of the circle of customers and the \tab \tab \tab \tab degree of similarity between activities before and after the transfer and the duration of any interruption in those \tab \tab \tab \tab \tab activities. It should be made clear, however, that each of these factors is only a part of the overall assessment \tab \tab \tab \tab \tab which is required and therefore they cannot be examined independently of each other.\'94}
\par \pard\plain \s0\nowidctlpar{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\cf0\kerning1\hich\af6\langfe2052\dbch\af7\afs24\lang1081\loch\f0\fs24\lang7177\ql{\i\hich\af4\dbch\af4\afs30\ai\rtlch \ltrch\loch\fs30\loch\f4
\tab \tab [65] In my view the position is that there will be cases where the transferor and the transferee agree that the workforce will be \tab \tab taken over by the transferee but the transaction cannot be described as a transfer of the business as a going concern if many \tab \tab of the other factors that are relevant to a transfer being one as a going concern are absent and there will be transactions \tab \tab \tab where the transferor and the transferee will agree that the workforce will not be taken over but the transaction will still amount \tab \tab to a transfer of a business as a going concern because of the presence of many or all of the other factors that go to making a \tab \tab transfer of a business to be one as a going concern. Accordingly each transaction must, in my view, be considered on its own \tab \tab merits in the light of all the surrounding circumstances of the transaction before a determination can be made whether it \tab \tab \tab constitutes a transfer of a business as going concern.\'94 }
